Then‚ on the plastered wall behind the young monk is an oval portrait of Alexander the Sixth‚ the tremendous Borgia, that prodigy of crime and power—his face, what a contrast to the wasted boy's beneath! he is sat and flourishing‚ rosy and full of blood and of the pride os life, insolent and at his ease; Luther like a young branch all but withered in the leaves of his spring—the Vicar of God spreading like a green hay tree. He is holding up his two first fingers in the Apostolic benediction‚ with a something between a scowl and a leer—all this rendered, and yet nothing overdone. This portrait hangs on a rude drawing of the Crucifixion‚ as if by a young and adoring hand, full of feeling and with a touching uncertainty in the lines, as if the hand that traced it was unaccustomed and trembling; it conceals our Saviour’s sace.
